-- Why Duplication Exists: Bills per Report --
  opensecrets_extraction.py splits report spend equally across all bills.
  A firm mentioning the same bill in 3 different reports produces
  3 rows for that (firm, bill) pair.

  Worst case: BLACKSTONE GROUP × S.1895
    → 20 rows for this single (firm, bill) pair
    Row amounts: [20000, 7500, 7500, 23333, 440000, 23333, 7500, 10000, 18750, 10000, 10000, 20000, 7500, 12000, 0, 10000, 15000, 18750, 7500, 18750]
    Sum (true total allocated spend): $687,417

-- Zero-Budget Firms --
  Firms with total reported spend = $0:  1
    TREEHOUSE FOODS  (0 unique bills filed)
  → These firms produce NaN fracs and are excluded before
    cosine and RBO similarity computation.

-- Post-Aggregation (groupby sum) --
  Rows after aggregation: 7,136
  (was 25,676 rows — 3.6x reduction)
  Total spend preserved:  $1,446,687,394  (should match raw = $1,734,019,367)

-- Summary --
  Raw data has 25,676 rows for 7,136 unique (firm, bill)
  pairs — an average of 3.60 rows per pair.
  This is correct: opensecrets_extraction.py creates one row per bill per report.
  Aggregation before network construction collapses to true totals.

